<h2>A Triangle Inequality</h2>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Billiards in triangles, which do not have the nice right-angled geometry of rectangles, is more complicated. As you might remember from high school geometry, there are several kinds of triangles: acute triangles, where all three internal angles are less than 90 degrees; right triangles, which have a 90-degree angle; and obtuse triangles, which have one angle that is more than 90 degrees.</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216afe6b' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216afe6b","data":{"id":135509,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","alt":"","class":"","width":0,"height":0,"mobileSrc":{"ID":135508,"id":135508,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":31707,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:50:50","modified":"2024-02-15 15:50:50","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":"default","disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":{"ID":135509,"id":135509,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","filesize":16422,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-desktop\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-desktop","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:51:09","modified":"2024-02-15 15:51:09","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Billiard tables shaped like acute and right triangles have periodic trajectories. But no one knows if the same is true for obtuse triangles.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">To find a periodic trajectory in an acute triangle, draw a perpendicular line from each vertex to the opposite side, as seen to the left, below. Join the points where the right angles occur to form a triangle, as seen on the right.</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b0b32' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216b0b32","data":{"id":"","src":"","alt":"","class":"","width":"","height":"","mobileSrc":{"ID":135511,"id":135511,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":26864,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_6-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_6-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:52:27","modified":"2024-02-15 15:52:27","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_6-560-Mobile.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":"default","disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":false,"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">This inscribed triangle is a periodic billiard trajectory called the Fagnano orbit, named for Giovanni Fagnano, who in 1775 showed that this triangle has the smallest perimeter of all inscribed triangles.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In the early 1990s, Fred Holt at the University of Washington and </span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://www.ux1.eiu.edu/~cfgg/">Gregory Galperin</a></span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and his collaborators at Moscow State University </span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01264095">independently</a></span> <span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://www.mathnet.ru/php/archive.phtml?wshow=paper&amp;jrnid=rm&amp;paperid=4511&amp;option_lang=eng">showed</a></span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> that every right triangle has periodic orbits. One simple way to show this is to reflect the triangle about one leg and then the other, as shown below. </span></p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b1a1f' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216b1a1f","data":{"id":"","src":"","alt":"","class":"","width":"","height":"","mobileSrc":{"ID":135513,"id":135513,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":567740,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_8-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_8-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:53:44","modified":"2024-02-15 15:53:44","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_8-560-Mobile.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":"default","disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":false,"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Start with a trajectory that’s at a right angle to the hypotenuse (the long side of the triangle). The hypotenuse and its second reflection are parallel, so a perpendicular line segment joining them corresponds to a trajectory that will bounce back and forth forever: The ball departs the hypotenuse at a right angle, bounces off both legs, returns to the hypotenuse at a right angle, and then retraces its route.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">But obtuse triangles remain a mystery. In their 1992 paper, Galperin and his collaborators came up with a variety of methods of reflecting obtuse triangles in a way that lets you create periodic orbits, but the methods only worked for some special cases. Then, in 2008, <a href="http://www.math.brown.edu/reschwar/papers.html">Richard Schwartz</a> at Brown University showed that all obtuse triangles with <a href="https://projecteuclid.org/journals/experimental-mathematics/volume-18/issue-2/Obtuse-Triangular-Billiards-II--One-Hundred-Degrees-Worth-of/em/1259158426.full">angles of 100 degrees or less</a> contain a periodic trajectory. His approach involved breaking the problem down into multiple cases and verifying each case using traditional mathematics and computer assistance. In 2018, Jacob Garber, Boyan Marinov, <a href="https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~kjmoore/">Kenneth Moore</a> and George Tokarsky at the University of Alberta <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1808.06667#:~:text=In%202006%2C%20Schwartz%20showed%20that,using%20a%20computer%20assisted%20proof.">extended this threshold</a> to 112.3 degrees. (Tokarsky and Marinov <a href="https://gwtokarsky.github.io/">had spent more than a decade</a> chasing this goal.)</p>
<h2 style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>A Topological Turn</strong></h2>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Another approach has been used to show that if all the angles are rational — that is, they can be expressed as fractions — obtuse triangles with even bigger angles must have periodic trajectories. Instead of just copying a polygon on a flat plane, this approach maps copies of polygons onto topological surfaces, doughnuts with one or more holes in them.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">If you reflect a rectangle over its short side, and then reflect both rectangles over their longest side, making four versions of the original rectangle, and then glue the top and bottom together and the left and right together, you will have made a doughnut, or torus, as shown below. Billiard trajectories on the table correspond to trajectories on the torus, and vice versa.</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b3868' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216b3868","data":{"id":135516,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","alt":"","class":"","width":0,"height":0,"mobileSrc":{"ID":135515,"id":135515,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":818566,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_9-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_9-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:54:34","modified":"2024-02-15 15:54:34","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Mobile.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":"default","disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":{"ID":135516,"id":135516,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","filesize":14265,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_9-560-desktop\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_9-560-desktop","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:54:48","modified":"2024-02-15 15:54:48","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_9-560-Desktop.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">In a landmark 1986 article, <a href="https://mscs.uic.edu/profiles/masur/">Howard Masur</a> used this technique to show that all polygonal tables with rational angles have periodic orbits. His approach worked not only for obtuse triangles, but for far more complicated shapes: Irregular 100-sided tables, say, or polygons whose walls zig and zag creating nooks and crannies, have periodic orbits, so long as the angles are rational.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Somewhat remarkably, the existence of one periodic orbit in a polygon implies the existence of infinitely many; shifting the trajectory by just a little bit will yield a family of related periodic trajectories.</p>
<h2 style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>The Illumination Problem</strong></h2>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Shapes with nooks and crannies give rise to a related question. Rather than asking about trajectories that return to their starting point, this problem asks whether trajectories can visit every point on a given table. This is called the illumination problem because we can think about it by imagining a laser beam reflecting off mirrored walls enclosing the billiard table. We ask if, given two points on a particular table, you can always shine a laser (idealized as an infinitely thin ray of light) from one point to the other. To put it another way, if we placed a light bulb, which shines in all directions at once, at some point on the table, would it light up the whole room?</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b40db' class='related-list'><script type="text/template">{"type":"LinkList","id":"component-65d3b216b40db","data":{"title":"Related:","class":"related-list","links":[{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/maryam-mirzakhani-is-first-woman-fields-medalist-20140812\/","title":"A Tenacious Explorer of Abstract Surfaces"},{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/in-praise-of-simple-problems-20180109\/","title":"In Praise of Simple Problems"},{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/new-shapes-solve-infinite-pool-table-problem-20170808\/","title":"New Shapes Solve Infinite Pool-Table Problem"}]}}</script></div>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">There have been two main lines of research into the problem: finding shapes that can’t be illuminated and proving that large classes of shapes can be. Whereas finding oddball shapes that can’t be illuminated can be done through a clever application of simple math, proving that a lot of shapes can be illuminated has only been possible through the use of heavy mathematical machinery.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">In 1958, <a href="https://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/people/roger-penrose">Roger Penrose</a>, a mathematician who went on to win the <a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2020/penrose/facts/">2020 Nobel Prize in Physics</a>, found a curved table in which any point in one region couldn’t illuminate any point in another region. For decades, nobody could come up with a polygon that had the same property. But in 1995, Tokarsky used a simple fact about triangles to create a blockish 26-sided polygon with two points that are mutually inaccessible, shown below. That is, a laser beam shot from one point, regardless of its direction, cannot hit the other point.</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b4d87' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216b4d87","data":{"id":"","src":"","alt":"","class":"","width":"","height":"","mobileSrc":{"ID":135518,"id":135518,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":395199,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_10-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_10-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:55:39","modified":"2024-02-15 15:55:39","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","1536x1536-width":1,"1536x1536-height":1,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","2048x2048-width":1,"2048x2048-height":1,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","square_small-width":1,"square_small-height":1,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_10-560-Mobile.svg","square_large-width":1,"square_large-height":1}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":"default","disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":false,"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p>The key idea that Tokarsky used when building his special table was that if a laser beam starts at one of the acute angles in a 45°-45°-90° triangle, it can never return to that corner.</p>
<div id='component-65d3b216b6938' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-65d3b216b6938","data":{"id":135522,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Desktop.svg","alt":"","class":"","width":0,"height":0,"mobileSrc":{"ID":135523,"id":135523,"title":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile","filename":"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","filesize":152590,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_11-560-mobile\/","alt":"","author":"52094","description":"","caption":"","name":"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_11-560-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":135408,"date":"2024-02-15 15:57:38","modified":"2024-02-15 15:57:38","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/svg+xml","type":"image","subtype":"svg+xml","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":0,"height":0,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","thumbnail-width":1,"thumbnail-height":1,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","medium-width":1,"medium-height":1,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","medium_large-width":1,"medium_large-height":1,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_11-560-Mobile.svg","large-width":1,"large-height":1,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2024\/02\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_