ng off a wall, for the ball to return to its starting point traveling in the same direction, its trajectory must cross the table an even number of times in both directions. So \u003cem>m \u003c/em>and \u003cem>n \u003c/em>must be even. Lay out a grid of identical rectangles, each viewed as a mirror image of its neighbors. Draw a line segment from a point on the original table to the identical point on a copy \u003cem>n\u003c/em> tables away in the long direction and \u003cem>m\u003c/em> tables away in the short direction. Adjust the original point slightly if the path passes through a corner. Here’s an example where \u003cem>n\u003c/em> = 2 and \u003cem>m\u003c/em> = 6. When folded back up, the path produces a periodic trajectory, as shown in the green rectangle.\u003c/span>\u003c/p>\n\u003cdiv id='component-65d3b216ae485' class=''>\u003cscript type=\"text/template\">{\"type\":\"Image\",\"id\":\"component-65d3b216ae485\",\"data\":{\"id\":135533,\"src\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Desktop.svg\",\"alt\":\"\",\"class\":\"\",\"width\":0,\"height\":0,\"mobileSrc\":{\"ID\":135532,\"id\":135532,\"title\":\"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Mobile\",\"filename\":\"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Mobile.svg\",\"filesize\":188803,\"url\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Mobile.svg\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v3_fig_4-560-mobile\\/\",\"alt\":\"\",\"author\":\"52094\",\"description\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"name\":\"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v3_fig_4-560-mobile\",\"status\":\"inherit\",\"uploaded_to\":135408,\"date\":\"2024-02-15 23:32:52\",\"modified\":\"2024-02-15 23:32:52\",\"menu_order\":0,\"mime_type\":\"image\\/svg+xml\",\"type\":\"image\",\"subtype\":\"svg+xm