\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Desktop.svg\",\"square_small-width\":1,\"square_small-height\":1,\"square_large\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v3_Fig_4-560-Desktop.svg\",\"square_large-width\":1,\"square_large-height\":1}},\"largeForPrint\":false,\"externalLink\":\"\",\"original_resolution\":false}}\u003c\/script>\u003c/div>\n\u003ch2>A Triangle Inequality\u003c/h2>\n\u003cp style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Billiards in triangles, which do not have the nice right-angled geometry of rectangles, is more complicated. As you might remember from high school geometry, there are several kinds of triangles: acute triangles, where all three internal angles are less than 90 degrees; right triangles, which have a 90-degree angle; and obtuse triangles, which have one angle that is more than 90 degrees.\u003c/p>\n\u003cdiv id='component-65d3b216afe6b' class=''>\u003cscript type=\"text/template\">{\"type\":\"Image\",\"id\":\"component-65d3b216afe6b\",\"data\":{\"id\":135509,\"src\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Desktop.svg\",\"alt\":\"\",\"class\":\"\",\"width\":0,\"height\":0,\"mobileSrc\":{\"ID\":135508,\"id\":135508,\"title\":\"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile\",\"filename\":\"PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg\",\"filesize\":31707,\"url\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/02\\/PolygonalBililardsbyMerrillSherman-v2_Fig_5-560-Mobile.svg\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/the-mysterious-math-of-billiards-tables-20240215\\/polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-mobile\\/\",\"alt\":\"\",\"author\":\"52094\",\"description\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"name\":\"polygonalbililardsbymerrillsherman-v2_fig_5-560-mobile\",\"status\":\"inherit\",\"uploaded_t